ata.parliament.uk/resources/536151/answer","Biography information for David Mowat","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/536151/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/536151/answer",,,,,"17","Health","Health","2016-07-13","General Practitioners: Halton","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Health, how many full-time equivalent GPs were employed in Halton Clinical Commissioning Group area in each year since 2012.","false","Biography information for Derek Twigg","Halton","Derek Twigg","42649"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/536152","Department of Health","false","2016-07-18","<p>The cross-Government Suicide Prevention Strategy (2012) identifies people under the care of mental health services as a high risk group. We have made significant progress in this area over the last decade with the number of inpatient deaths by suicide reducing by more than half. However, we recognise that the number of suicides in people under the care of mental health services in the community has been increasing.</p><p> </p><p>We have implemented the Mental Health Crisis Care Concordat and now every local area has a crisis care action plan in place. We are also investing an additional £1 billion in mental health over the next five years which includes £290 million to improve perinatal mental health, £247 million to improve liaison mental health services in emergency departments and over £400 million to enable 24/7 treatment in communities as a safe and effective alternative to hospital.</p><p> </p><p>We have accepted the recommendations of the independent Mental Health Taskforce’s Five Year Forward View for Mental Health to reduce the national suicide rate by 10% by 2020/21, local areas to implement multi-agency suicide prevention action plans by 2017 and to take steps so that lessons are learned from all suicides in NHS-funded mental health settings to prevent future deaths.</p><p> </p><p>We will publish the annual progress report to the cross-Government strategy later this year which will set out ways we are strengthening the strategy, including how we can reduce suicides in high risk groups.</p>","Oxford West and Abingdon","Nicola Blackwood",,"2016-07-18T14:47:19.93Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/536152/answer","Biography information for Baroness Blackwood of North Oxford","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/536152/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/536152/answer",,,,,"17","Health","Health","2016-07-13","Mental Health Services","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Health, what assessment he has made of the implications for his policies on NHS services provision of the findings in the article entitled, Mental health services, suicide and 7-day working, published in the British Journal of Psychiatry in July 2016, related to suicides at weekends.","false","Biography information for Steve McCabe","Birmingham, Selly Oak","Steve McCabe","42629"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/536153","Department of Health","false","2016-07-18","<p>Promoting the best possible care for all people with diabetes is a key priority for this Government.</p><p> </p><p>Patient education will play a crucial part in empowering all people with diabetes to manage their condition more effectively and help avoid complications in the future. We know there is much further to go in the proportion of people with diabetes attending structured education programmes. The Department, NHS England and Diabetes UK are currently looking at a number of ways to improve take up.</p>","Oxford West and Abingdon","Nicola Blackwood",,"2016-07-18T15:03:22.773Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/536153/answer","Biography information for Baroness Blackwood of North Oxford","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/536153/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/536153/answer",,,,,"17","Health","Health","2016-07-13","Diabetes: Health Education","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Health, if he will provide support to employers to encourage people diagnosed with Type 1 diabetes to attend a diabetes education course soon after they are diagnosed.","false","Biography information for Mr Jamie Reed","Copeland","Mr Jamie Reed","42636"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/536154","Department of Health","false","2016-07-18","<p>No estimate has been made of the annual cost to people with Type 1 diabetes who self-fund a continuous glucose monitor.</p><p> </p><p>In August 2015, the National Institute for Health and Care Excellence provided updated guidelines for both Type 1 diabetes and for children and young people with diabetes. In both, the cost effectiveness, as well as the clinical effectiveness, of continuous glucose monitoring was assessed. Both sets of guidelines outline specific clinical situations where the clinical and cost effectiveness justify consideration of the use of the technology.</p>","Oxford West and Abingdon","Nicola Blackwood","42741","2016-07-18T14:55:09.08Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/536154/answer","Biography information for Baroness Blackwood of North Oxford","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/536154/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/536154/answer",,,,,"17","Health","Health","2016-07-13","Diabetes: Medical Equipment","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Health, what estimate his Department has made of the annual cost to people with Type 1 diabetes who self-fund a continuous glucose monitor.","false","Biography information for Mr Jamie Reed","Copeland","Mr Jamie Reed","42637"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/536155","Department of Health","false","2016-07-20","<p>Details of all Ministerial meetings with external stakeholders are published quarterly in arrears on the GOV.UK website. The latest publication which covers meetings between January and March 2016 can be found at:</p><p> </p><p><a href="https://www.gov.uk/government/publications/ministerial-gifts-hospitality-travel-and-external-meetings-2016" target="_blank">https://www.gov.uk/government/publications/ministerial-gifts-hospitality-travel-and-external-meetings-2016</a></p>","Oxford West and Abingdon","Nicola Blackwood",,"2016-07-20T14:22:21.127Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/536155/answer","Biography information for Baroness Blackwood of North Oxford","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/536155/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/536155/answer",,,,,"17","Health","Health","2016-07-13","Obesity","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Health, what recent discussions he has had with the Food and Drink Federation on tackling obesity.","false","Biography information for Jim Shannon","Strangford","Jim Shannon","42610"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/536156","Department of Health","false","2016-07-20","<p>The Department has had no specific discussions with NHS England on this topic.</p>","Warrington South","David Mowat",,"2016-07-20T13:35:45.797Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/536156/answer","Biography information for David Mowat","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/536156/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/536156/answer",,,,,"17","Health","Health","2016-07-13","Cancer: Medical Treatments","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Health, what discussions he has had with NHS England on support for research into immuno-oncology treatments for head and neck cancer.","false","Biography information for Jim Shannon","Strangford","Jim Shannon","42614"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/536157","Department of Health","false","2016-07-20","<p>AF-219 is still undergoing clinical trials for the treatment of chronic coughs and it would be premature to comment on its future availability on the National Health Service.</p>","Oxford West and Abingdon","Nicola Blackwood",,"2016-07-20T14:21:32.343Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/536157/answer","Biography information for Baroness Blackwood of North Oxford","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/536157/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/536157/answer",,,,,"17","Health","Health","2016-07-13","AF-219","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Health, if he will assess the potential merits of making the drug AK-219 available on the NHS to treat persistent coughs.","false","Biography information for Jim Shannon","Strangford","Jim Shannon","42611"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/536158","Department of Health","false","2016-07-21","<p>In November 2015 the Joint Committee for Vaccination and Immunisation advised that a human papillomavirus (HPV) vaccination programme should be introduced for men who have sex with men (MSM) attending genito-urinary medicine clinics. In preparing this advice, the Committee took into account mathematical models that considered the likely effect of the vaccination programme on anal, penile and oropharyngeal (including tonsillar) cancers. The models suggested that introduction of HPV vaccination for MSM is likely to decrease the incidence of oropharyngeal cancers in the long term.</p>","Oxford West and Abingdon","Nicola Blackwood",,"2016-07-21T14:42:21.18Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/536158/answer","Biography information for Baroness Blackwood of North Oxford","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/536158/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/536158/answer",,,,,"17","Health","Health","2016-07-13","Cancer: Males","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Health, what assessment he has had made of the effect of the introduction of the HPV vaccination on reducing the incidence of head and neck cancer among men who have sex with men.","false","Biography information for Jim Shannon","Strangford","Jim Shannon","42613"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/536159","Department of Health","false","2016-07-18","<p>Obesity is a complex problem with many factors having an impact. For this reason, it is important to ensure that the Childhood Obesity Strategy is as comprehensive as possible. The Prime Minister and the Cabinet will be working over the coming days and weeks to establish their priorities and how we deliver on these commitments.</p>","Oxford West and Abingdon","Nicola Blackwood",,"2016-07-18T15:15:57.4Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/536159/answer","Biography information for Baroness Blackwood of North Oxford","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/536159/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/536159/answer",,,,,"17","Health","Health","2016-07-13","Obesity: Children","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Health, pursuant to the Answer of 11 July 2016 to Question 41992, what the reasons are for the time taken to publish the childhood obesity strategy; and if he will make a statement.","false","Biography information for Helen Jones","Warrington North","Helen Jones","42588"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/536160","Department of Health","false","2016-07-20","<p>In the majority of men, the prostate grows larger with age, and patients usually present to a general practitioner with symptoms of an enlarged prostate after the age of 50. Symptoms can include: weak urine flow; needing to urinate more often, especially at night; a feeling that your bladder has not emptied properly; and, difficulty starting to urinate. Some men find their symptoms are manageable and cause few problems, other find their symptoms worsening, which can impact on wellbeing and quality of life.</p><p> </p><p>For patients who need treatment, there are a number of approaches available including lifestyle and dietary adjustments, medicines and surgery.</p>","Warrington South","David Mowat",,"2016-07-20T16:13:36.423Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/536160/answer","Biography information for David Mowat","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/536160/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/536160/answer",,,,,"17","Health","Health","2016-07-13","Prostate Gland","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Health, what steps he is taking to reduce the incidence of people being diagnosed with enlarged prostates.","false","Biography information for Jim Shannon","Strangford","Jim Shannon","42612"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/536161","Department of Health","false","2016-07-20","<p>The Department has no plans to make such an assessment.</p>","Oxford West and Abingdon","Nicola Blackwood",,"2016-07-20T14:23:23.977Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/536161/answer","Biography information for Baroness Blackwood of North Oxford","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/536161/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/536161/answer",,,,,"17","Health","Health","2016-07-13","Organs: Transplant Surgery","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Health, if he will make an assessment of the potential merits of the use of pig organ transplants for humans.","false","Biography information for Jim Shannon","Strangford","Jim Shannon","42618"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/536162","Department of Health","false","2016-07-21","<p>Many new medicines in Europe, including medicines to treat breast cancer, are licensed by the European Medicines Agency (EMA). The EMA brings together scientific experts from across Europe by working closely with the national regulatory authorities, in a partnership known as the <a href="http://www.ema.europa.eu/ema/index.jsp?curl=pages/about_us/general/general_content_000671.jsp&amp;mid=WC0b01ac05809f8ed0" target="_blank">European medicines regulatory network</a>. The Medicines and Healthcare products Regulatory Agency is an active participant in this network and its discussions.</p>","Oxford West and Abingdon","Nicola Blackwood",,"2016-07-21T14:37:29.963Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/536162/answer","Biography information for Baroness Blackwood of North Oxford","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/536162/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/536162/answer",,,,,"17","Health","Health","2016-07-13","Breast Cancer: Drugs","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Health, what discussions he has had with his EU counterparts on co-operation on developing and making available new drugs to treat breast cancer.","false","Biography information for Jim Shannon","Strangford","Jim Shannon","42619"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/536163","Department of Health","false","2016-07-20","<p>The Department has frequent discussions with representatives of the United Kingdom pharmaceutical industry as well as with individual pharmaceutical companies on a range of topics. We want to see the latest and most advanced drugs made available to National Health Service patients in a way that ensures value for money.</p>","Oxford West and Abingdon","Nicola Blackwood",,"2016-07-20T14:22:32.243Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/536163/answer","Biography information for Baroness Blackwood of North Oxford","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/536163/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/536163/answer",,,,,"17","Health","Health","2016-07-13","Cancer: Drugs","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Health, what discussions he has had with pharmaceutical companies on steps to reduce the cost of cancer drugs for the NHS.","false","Biography information for Jim Shannon","Strangford","Jim Shannon","42620"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/536164","Department of Health","false","2016-07-20","<p>The information is not held in the format requested.</p>","Warrington South","David Mowat",,"2016-07-20T16:59:00.627Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/536164/answer","Biography information for David Mowat","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/536164/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/536164/answer",,,,,"17","Health","Health","2016-07-13","Lung Diseases: Diagnosis","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Health, how many people in each age group were diagnosed with lung disease in each of the last five years.","false","Biography information for Jim Shannon","Strangford","Jim Shannon","42621"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/536165","Department of Health","false","2016-07-20","<p>It is the responsibility of the professional regulators, such as the General Medical Council (GMC), to set the standards and outcomes for education and training and approve training curricula to ensure newly qualified healthcare professionals are equipped with the knowledge, skills and attitudes to provide high quality patient care. This includes training in the treatment of people with chronic diseases.</p><p> </p><p>Higher Education Institutions are responsible for ensuring the programmes they provide allow healthcare students to meet the outcomes set out by the regulators upon graduation.</p><p> </p><p>The Royal Colleges, for example the Royal College of Nursing, the Royal College of General Practitioners and the Royal College of Surgeons, also have responsibility for developing curricula for doctors and nurses, in particular postgraduate curricula.</p><p> </p><p>In England, Health Education England works with bodies that set curricula such as the GMC and the Royal Colleges to seek to ensure training meets the needs of patients, including those with chronic diseases.</p>","Ludlow","Mr Philip Dunne",,"2016-07-20T14:00:21.553Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/536165/answer","Biography information for Mr Philip Dunne","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/536165/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/536165/answer",,,,,"17","Health","Health","2016-07-13","Chronic Illnesses: Medical Treatments","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Health, if he will take steps to improve the training available to medical practitioners on the treatment of people with chronic diseases.","false","Biography information for Jim Shannon","Strangford","Jim Shannon","42617"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/536166","Department of Health","false","2016-07-20","<p>The data requested is not collected.</p>","Warrington South","David Mowat",,"2016-07-20T16:14:24.807Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/536166/answer","Biography information for David Mowat","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/536166/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/536166/answer",,,,,"17","Health","Health","2016-07-13","Back Pain: Diagnosis","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Health, how many people in each age group were diagnosed with back pain in each of the last five years.","false","Biography information for Jim Shannon","Strangford","Jim Shannon","42615"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/536167","Department of Health","false","2016-07-20","<p>The Department does not hold the information to answer this question. This data has been provided by the National Health Service Litigation Authority.</p><p> </p><p>In 2014/15 (the most recent year for which information has been published) 11,497 new clinical negligence claims were received by the NHS Litigation Authority which indemnifies all English National Health Service trusts, clinical commissioning groups and some independent sector providers. This number therefore includes claims related to organisations other than NHS hospitals. Claims can arise some years after an incident so this number represents the number of claims notified to Members in 2014/15 regardless of when the incident occurred. Not all these claims will result in financial compensation being awarded to the claimant.</p><p> </p><p>This information is available on the NHS Litigation Authority’s website in Fact sheets:</p><p> </p><p>www.nhsla.com/CurrentActivity/Pages/Home.aspx</p>","Warrington South","David Mowat",,"2016-07-20T16:15:39.523Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/536167/answer","Biography information for David Mowat","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/536167/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/536167/answer",,,,,"17","Health","Health","2016-07-13","NHS: Negligence","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Health, how many compensation claims have been made against NHS hospitals related to treatment received by patients.","false","Biography information for Jim Shannon","Strangford","Jim Shannon","42616"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/536168","Home Office","false","2016-07-21","<p>In June 2016 The Home Office received the All-Party Parliamentary Group (APPG) for International Freedom of Religion’s report, ‘Fleeing persecution: Asylum claims in the UK on religious freedom grounds’. We are carefully considering the report and its recommendations and will provide a response in due course, including whether we will consider whether any changes to the way we handle religious-based claims are appropriate.</p><p>The report acknowledges the progress made by the Home Office with regards to guidance and training provided to its staff but highlighted the Group’s view that there were some discrepancies between the Home Office policy and practice.</p><p>The Home Office carefully considers all asylum claims on their individual merits and grants protection for those who genuinely need it, in accordance with our international obligations under the Refugee Convention and the European Convention on Human Rights (ECHR). In every asylum case the particular circumstances of the individual are considered in light of published country information, which includes issues relating specifically to religious freedoms.</p><p>Published guidance on the interviewing and consideration of religious claims is regularly reviewed and takes into consideration the views of religious groups and other stakeholders.</p>","Scarborough and Whitby","Mr Robert Goodwill",,"2016-07-21T15:44:53.927Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/536168/answer","Biography information for Mr Robert Goodwill","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/536168/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/536168/answer",,,,,"1","Home Office","Home Office","2016-07-13","Asylum: Religious Freedom","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for the Home Department, what representations she has received on reforming the questions asked on asylum applications related to persecution related to religious beliefs.","false","Biography information for Jim Shannon","Strangford","Jim Shannon","42622"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/536169","Home Office","false","2016-07-18","<p>Protecting the public is a priority for this Government and it is important that checks undertaken are thorough; a proportion of the applications received by the DBS must be referred to one or more police forces as part of the enhanced disclosure process. In the vast majority of cases these checks are completed within target.</p><p>Whilst no assessment has been made of the impact of timeliness on sporting activities, it is recognised that delays may create problems for some people. We will not compromise when it comes to the safety of children and vulnerable adults.</p>","Hemel Hempstead","Mike Penning",,"2016-07-18T09:16:59.353Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/536169/answer","Biography information for Sir Mike Penning","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/536169/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/536169/answer",,,,,"1","Home Office","Home Office","2016-07-13","Vetting: Sports","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for the Home Department, what discussions she has had with the Secretary of State for Culture, Media and Sport on the potential effect of delays in the processing of criminal record check disclosures on sporting activities.","false","Biography information for Tom Brake","Carshalton and Wallington","Tom Brake","42625"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/536170","Home Office","false","2016-07-18","<p>The Disclosure and Barring Service is responsible for issuing criminal record certificates and the maintenance of children’s and adults’ barred lists. The Disclosure and Barring Service has a target of processing 85% of all disclosure applications within 21 days. In the vast majority of cases (95%), disclosure certificates are issued within 8 weeks (2015/16).</p><p>Criminal record certificates issued by the Disclosure and Barring Service do not expire after a specific period of time and do not include a renewal date. A certificate has no set period of validity. Information revealed through a Disclosure and Barring Service check reflects the information that was available at the time of its issue. Disclosure certificates are primarily designed to be used by an employer at the point of recruitment for a particular position.</p><p>Some roles and some employers require the person concerned to “renew” their Disclosure and Barring Service check at specific intervals. The person can do that either by applying for a new certificate or by using the Disclosure and Barring Service Update Service.</p><p>It would not be appropriate to comment on specific cases, but there are a number of factors which can affect the timely completion of checks. These include the length of time if can take for an employer to deal with the initial application, the accurate completion of the application form, the clarity of the information provided, the existence of conviction or non-conviction information, legal challenges and the operational effectiveness of the disclosure units of the police forces involved, if any, in the enhanced process. In some cases, forces will ask Disclosure and Barring Service to clarify some details provided by the applicant which requires further investigation and this can cause further delays.</p>","Hemel Hempstead","Mike Penning","42591 ; 42724","2016-07-18T09:18:28.067Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/536170/answer","Biography information for Sir Mike Penning","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/536170/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/536170/answer",,,,,"1","Home Office","Home Office","2016-07-13","Vetting","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for the Home Department, how many Disclosure and Barring Service renewal applications were made prior to the renewal date and issued after the applicants' certificate expired in the last 12 months.","false","Biography information for Rosie Cooper","West Lancashire","Rosie Cooper","42590"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/536171","Home Office","false","2016-07-18","<p>The Disclosure and Barring Service is responsible for issuing criminal record certificates and the maintenance of children’s and adults’ barred lists. The Disclosure and Barring Service has a target of processing 85% of all disclosure applications within 21 days. In the vast majority of cases (95%), disclosure certificates are issued within 8 weeks (2015/16).</p><p>Criminal record certificates issued by the Disclosure and Barring Service do not expire after a specific period of time and do not include a renewal date. A certificate has no set period of validity. Information revealed through a Disclosure and Barring Service check reflects the information that was available at the time of its issue. Disclosure certificates are primarily designed to be used by an employer at the point of recruitment for a particular position.</p><p>Some roles and some employers require the person concerned to “renew” their Disclosure and Barring Service check at specific intervals. The person can do that either by applying for a new certificate or by using the Disclosure and Barring Service Update Service.</p><p>It would not be appropriate to comment on specific cases, but there are a number of factors which can affect the timely completion of checks. These include the length of time if can take for an employer to deal with the initial application, the accurate completion of the application form, the clarity of the information provided, the existence of conviction or non-conviction information, legal challenges and the operational effectiveness of the disclosure units of the police forces involved, if any, in the enhanced process. In some cases, forces will ask Disclosure and Barring Service to clarify some details provided by the applicant which requires further investigation and this can cause further delays.</p>","Hemel Hempstead","Mike Penning","42590 ; 42724","2016-07-18T09:18:28.117Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/536171/answer","Biography information for Sir Mike Penning","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/536171/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/536171/answer",,,,,"1","Home Office","Home Office","2016-07-13","Vetting","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for the Home Department, how many Disclosure and Barring Service checks are yet to be processed which are (a) one, (b) three and (c) six months after the relevant renewal date.","false","Biography information for Rosie Cooper","West Lancashire","Rosie Cooper","42591"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/536172","Home Office","false","2016-07-18","<p>Where an asylum claim is lodged in France by a minor with close family connections to the UK, both governments are committed to ensuring that process are in place to expedite reunification. Under the UK-France Joint Declaration of 20 August 2015, the UK and France have committed to ensuring that the provisions of the Dublin III Regulation are used efficiently and effectively. To assist the handling of such cases, the two Governments have established a permanent official contact group, agreed single points of contact within respective Dublin Units and the UK has seconded an asylum expert to the French administration to improve all stages of the process of identifying, protecting and transferring relevant cases to the UK. We continue to work with the French Government to improve processes.</p>","Hemel Hempstead","Mike Penning",,"2016-07-18T09:15:36.953Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/536172/answer","Biography information for Sir Mike Penning","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/536172/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/536172/answer",,,,,"1","Home Office","Home Office","2016-07-13","Asylum: Children","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for the Home Department, pursuant to the Answer of 8 June 2016 to Question 37587, whether she is taking steps to reduce the time taken to process applications for the remaining children in refugee camps in Calais.","false","Biography information for Thangam Debbonaire","Bristol West","Thangam Debbonaire","42586"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/536173","Home Office","false","2016-07-20","<p>The rules setting out eligibility for integration loans are set out in the Integration loans for Refugees and Other Regulations 2007. All the factors set out in these Regulations are considered for each application received for an integration loan.</p><p>We do not intend to set a target time for processing loans less than the 28 day support period given to those granted refugee status. However processes are reviewed on a regular basis and the department aims to respond to all applications as quickly as possible.</p>","Scarborough and Whitby","Mr Robert Goodwill","42664","2016-07-20T14:11:09.743Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/536173/answer","Biography information for Mr Robert Goodwill","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/536173/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/536173/answer",,,,,"1","Home Office","Home Office","2016-07-13","Refugees: Loans","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for the Home Department, pursuant to the Answer of 8 June 2016 to Question 39223, what criteria officials of her Department have to follow to fulfil the aim of processing refugee integration loan applications as quickly as possible.","false","Biography information for Thangam Debbonaire","Bristol West","Thangam Debbonaire","42587"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/536174","Home Office","false","2016-07-20","<p>The Government has published the Terms of Reference for the Independent Review of Bulk Powers, which set out the composition of the review team. It was for David Anderson, as the independent reviewer to select the team best equipped to carry out the review and to critically appraise the need for bulk capabilities. David Anderson also published a summary for each member of the team setting out their experience and the diverse qualities which they will bring to the review.</p>","Wyre and Preston North","Mr Ben Wallace",,"2016-07-20T11:01:31.17Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/536174/answer","Biography information for Mr Ben Wallace","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/536174/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/536174/answer",,,,,"1","Home Office","Home Office","2016-07-13","Investigatory Powers Bill: Consultants","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for the Home Department, what arrangements were made for the declaration of (a) financial and (b) other interests by technical advisers to the independent review of the Investigatory Powers Bill before their appointment.","false","Biography information for Valerie  Vaz","Walsall South","Valerie Vaz","42644"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/536175","Home Office","false","2016-07-20","<p>We published guidance on the Modern Slavery Act on GOV.UK and a circular was sent to all bodies who are subject to the duty. We will publish data on notifications received and carry out further awareness-raising activity later this year.</p>","Truro and Falmouth","Sarah Newton","42652","2016-07-20T12:45:29.753Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/536175/answer","Biography information for Sarah Newton","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/536175/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/536175/answer",,,,,"1","Home Office","Home Office","2016-07-13","Slavery: Victims","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for the Home Department, what steps her Department has taken to raise awareness among public authorities of their statutory duty to notify her where they have reasonable grounds to believe that a person may be a victim of slavery or human trafficking under the Modern Slavery Act 2015.","false","Biography information for Sarah Champion","Rotherham","Sarah Champion","42651"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/536176","Home Office","false","2016-07-20","<p>We published guidance on the Modern Slavery Act on GOV.UK and a circular was sent to all bodies who are subject to the duty. We will publish data on notifications received and carry out further awareness-raising activity later this year.</p>","Truro and Falmouth","Sarah Newton","42651","2016-07-20T12:45:29.833Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/536176/answer","Biography information for Sarah Newton","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/536176/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/536176/answer",,,,,"1","Home Office","Home Office","2016-07-13","Slavery: Victims","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for the Home Department, how many notifications her Department has received under section 52 of the Modern Slavery Act 2015 relating to slavery or human trafficking of (a) children and (b) adults.","false","Biography information for Sarah Champion","Rotherham","Sarah Champion","42652"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/536177","Home Office","false","2016-07-18","<p>We are committed to ensuring we have an effective system for identifying and supporting victims. We reviewed and are piloting changes to the National Referral Mechanism. We will consider the introduction of regulations once the proposed changes to the National Referral Mechanism have been tested.</p>","Hemel Hempstead","Mike Penning",,"2016-07-18T09:17:17.553Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/536177/answer","Biography information for Sir Mike Penning","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/536177/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/536177/answer",,,,,"1","Home Office","Home Office","2016-07-13","Slavery: Victims","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for the Home Department, when she plans to bring forward proposals for secondary legislation on identifying and supporting victims under section 50 of the Modern Slavery Act 2015.","false","Biography information for Sarah Champion","Rotherham","Sarah Champion","42670"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/536179","Ministry of Justice","false","2016-07-18","<p>I refer the Hon Member to the answer given on 19 April (PQ 34222).</p><p> </p><p>The government’s response to the Harris Review was published in December 2015 and is available here: <a href="https://www.gov.uk/government/uploads/system/uploads/attachment_data/file/486564/gov-response-harris-review.pdf" target="_blank">https://www.gov.uk/government/uploads/system/uploads/attachment_data/file/486564/gov-response-harris-review.pdf</a></p><p>Work continues on implementation of those recommendations which the Government accepted which have not already been implemented.</p>","North East Hertfordshire","Sir Oliver Heald",,"2016-07-18T15:04:41.923Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/536179/answer","Biography information for Sir Oliver Heald","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/536179/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/536179/answer",,,,,"54","Justice","Justice","2016-07-13","Self-inflicted Deaths in Custody of 18-24 Year Olds Independent Review","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Justice, what progress her Department has made on implementation of the recommendations of the Harris Review.","false","Biography information for Rosie Cooper","West Lancashire","Rosie Cooper","42592"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/536180","Ministry of Justice","false","2016-07-22","<p>Sentencing Guidelines are issued by the Sentencing Council for England and Wales, a body independent of Government.</p>","East Surrey","Mr Sam Gyimah",,"2016-07-22T10:47:38.117Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/536180/answer","Biography information for Mr Sam Gyimah","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/536180/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/536180/answer",,,,,"54","Justice","Justice","2016-07-13","Slavery: Sentencing","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Justice, when she plans to publish the sentencing guidelines for Part 1 of the Modern Slavery Act 2015.","false","Biography information for Sarah Champion","Rotherham","Sarah Champion","42669"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/536181","Ministry of Justice","false","2016-07-22","<p>There have been no claims made under the Exclusivity Terms in Zero Hours Contracts (Redress) Regulations 2015 since its introduction on 11 January 2016 to 31 March 2016. Data from April 2016 onwards will be published in due course at <a href="https://www.gov.uk/government/collections/tribunals-statistics" target="_blank">https://www.gov.uk/government/collections/tribunals-statistics</a>.</p>","North East Hertfordshire","Sir Oliver Heald",,"2016-07-22T11:22:24.783Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/536181/answer","Biography information for Sir Oliver Heald","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/536181/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/536181/answer",,,,,"54","Justice","Justice","2016-07-13","Zero Hours Contracts","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Justice, how many employment tribunal claims have been made under the Exclusivity Terms in Zero Hours Contracts (Redress) Regulations 2015 since those regulations came into force.","false","Biography information for Justin Madders","Ellesmere Port and Neston","Justin Madders","42650"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/536182","Ministry of Justice","false","2016-07-22","<p>A parent is entitled to apply for an order under Schedule 1 of the Children Act 1989 regardless of marital status. Information on marital status is not collected in relation to Schedule 1 applications. Applications can also be made by a person who is a special guardian for the child or by a person with whom the child is living under a child arrangements order. The number of all applications issued under Schedule 1 over the period is set out in the table below.</p><p> </p><table><tbody><tr><td><p><strong>YEAR</strong></p></td><td><p><strong>No. of Applications</strong></p></td></tr><tr><td><p>2000</p></td><td><p>556</p></td></tr><tr><td><p>2001</p></td><td><p>604</p></td></tr><tr><td><p>2002</p></td><td><p>585</p></td></tr><tr><td><p>2003</p></td><td><p>599</p></td></tr><tr><td><p>2004</p></td><td><p>675</p></td></tr><tr><td><p>2005</p></td><td><p>677</p></td></tr><tr><td><p>2006</p></td><td><p>637</p></td></tr><tr><td><p>2007</p></td><td><p>702</p></td></tr><tr><td><p>2008</p></td><td><p>615</p></td></tr><tr><td><p>2009</p></td><td><p>507</p></td></tr><tr><td><p>2010</p></td><td><p>529</p></td></tr><tr><td><p>2011</p></td><td><p>472</p></td></tr><tr><td><p>2012</p></td><td><p>504</p></td></tr><tr><td><p>2013</p></td><td><p>467</p></td></tr><tr><td><p>2014</p></td><td><p>588</p></td></tr><tr><td><p>2015</p></td><td><p>650</p></td></tr></tbody></table><p> </p>","Bracknell","Dr Phillip Lee",,"2016-07-22T12:35:12.143Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/536182/answer","Biography information for Dr Phillip Lee","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/536182/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/536182/answer",,,,,"54","Justice","Justice","2016-07-13","Children: Maintenance","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Justice, how many applications have been issued in England and Wales for financial provision for the children of unmarried parents under schedule 1 of the Children Act 1989 in each year since 2000.","false","Biography information for David Mowat","Warrington South","David Mowat","42645"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/536183","Women and Equalities","false","2016-07-18","<p>The Equality and Human Rights Commission (EHRC) has and will continue to receive sufficient funds to enable it to fulfil its statutory functions. These functions include duties to promote and encourage equality and diversity and human rights, and powers for implementing inquiries, investigations and enforcement actions for equality and diversity. As now, the EHRC will continue to support people in individual cases where these are of strategic significance, for example in clarifying the relevant law.</p><p>Advice for individuals more generally is available from the Equality Advisory and Support Service, which is also funded by the Government.</p>","Gosport","Caroline Dinenage",,"2016-07-18T08:41:38.09Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/536183/answer","Biography information for Caroline Dinenage","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/536183/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/536183/answer",,,,,"31","Women and Equalities","Women and Equalities","2016-07-13","Equality and Human Rights Commission: Finance","1","House of Commons","To ask the Minister for Women and Equalities, what assessment her Department has carried out of the effect of proposed changes to the size of the budget for the Equality and Human Rights Commission on (a) the service it is able to support and (b) access to justice for (i) people who do not qualify for legal aid, (ii) people who cannot afford tribunal fees and (iii) people who do not have a local law centre or whose local Citizens Advice Bureau has closed.","false","Biography information for Mr Roger Godsiff","Birmingham, Hall Green","Mr Roger Godsiff","42631"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/536184","Home Office","false","2016-07-25","<p>The Independent Police Complaints Commission (IPCC) oversees the police complaints system in England and Wales. It is operationally independent of the police, government and complainants, and makes its decisions independently and free from political influence. It would therefore be inappropriate for me to discuss the IPCC’s decision. The Home Secretary does though plan to meet members of the Orgreave Truth and Justice Campaign immediately after the summer recess to discuss their case on the need for an inquiry into the events at Orgreave in 1984.</p>","Great Yarmouth","Brandon Lewis",,"2016-07-25T14:30:41.567Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/536184/answer","Biography information for Brandon Lewis","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/536184/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/536184/answer",,,,,"1","Home Office","Home Office","2016-07-13","Orgreave","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for the Home Department, if the Prime Minister will meet members of the Orgreave Truth and Justice Campaign to discuss the Independent Police Complaints Commission's decision not to make public the report into allegations of police misconduct at Orgreave in 1984.","false","Biography information for Tom Watson","West Bromwich East","Tom Watson","42626"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/536185","Department for Transport","false","2016-07-18","<p>Highways England, the Cumbria Local Enterprise Partnership, and Cumbria County Council commissioned a study to examine the connectivity, capability, resilience, and reliability of the A595. This will conclude later this month. Highways England has also commenced its evidence-based Route Strategy process. If this section of the A595 is included in the priority list, the next stage would be to consider potential improvement options, which would be developed during the next Road Investment Strategy (RIS) period (2020-2025).</p><p><strong> </strong></p>","South Holland and The Deepings","Mr John Hayes",,"2016-07-18T14:23:58Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/536185/answer","Biography information for Sir John Hayes","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/536185/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/536185/answer",,,,,"27","Transport","Transport","2016-07-13","A595","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Transport, if he will conduct a study on the potential merits and feasibility of upgrading the trunk road section of the A595 in 2016.","false","Biography information for Mr Jamie Reed","Copeland","Mr Jamie Reed","42628"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/536186","Department for Transport","false","2016-07-20","<p>We are working with train operators inside and outside of London, including through franchising arrangements, so that they maintain or increase the number of the stations which have been awarded ‘Secure Station’ status. The Secure Stations scheme is managed by the Department for Transport (DfT) and British Transport Police (BTP), and sets station design and management standards. It is aimed at:</p><p> </p><ul><li>preventing and reducing crime and disorder, providing a safer environment for passengers and staff;</li><li>increasing passenger numbers;</li><li>reducing costs of repair following vandalism, graffiti, etc., and of lost staff time due to distress or injury.</li></ul><p> </p><p>DfT is also currently working with the BTP to review and refresh the Secure Stations scheme to ensure that it continues to drive up standards, covers wider aspects of station security and that it reflects recent changes to the operating structure of the rail industry.</p>","Blackpool North and Cleveleys","Paul Maynard",,"2016-07-20T09:31:50.937Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/536186/answer","Biography information for Paul Maynard","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/536186/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/536186/answer",,,,,"27","Transport","Transport","2016-07-13","Railway Stations: Greater London","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Transport, what steps he is taking to improve the safety of passengers at train stations in London.","false","Biography information for Jim Shannon","Strangford","Jim Shannon","42603"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/536187","Wales Office","false","2016-07-19","<p>The M4 is one of Wales’ vital arteries and an important strategic route across Britain. It has been clear for some time that congestion on the M4 corridor around Newport is damaging the Welsh economy, and that an upgrade is urgently required. The Secretary of State for Wales met with the Welsh Government’s Cabinet Secretary for Economy and Infrastructure following his appointment to discuss options for upgrading the M4.</p><p> </p><p>The Welsh Government has announced that an independent public inquiry to examine its preferred route for the M4 relief road will commence in the Autumn. I look forward to seeing the inquiry’s findings and to a positive outcome to the benefit of both businesses and commuters.</p><p> </p>","Aberconwy","Guto Bebb",,"2016-07-19T09:58:54.657Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/536187/answer","Biography information for Guto Bebb","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/536187/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/536187/answer",,,,,"28","Wales","Wales","2016-07-13","M4: Wales","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Wales, what recent discussions his Department has had with members of the National Assembly for Wales on the proposed Blue Route M4 relief road.","false","Biography information for Dr Matthew Offord","Hendon","Dr Matthew Offord","42623"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/536188","Department for Business, Energy and Industrial Strategy","false","2016-08-10","<p>The Government has published an impact assessment on the introduction of the National Living Wage here: <a href="http://www.legislation.gov.uk/ukia/2016/3/pdfs/ukia_20160003_en.pdf" target="_blank">http://www.legislation.gov.uk/ukia/2016/3/pdfs/ukia_20160003_en.pdf</a></p><p> </p><p>In addition, more recent HM Treasury analysis[1] shows that the National Living Wage is expected to eradicate the gender pay gap for the lowest paid (at the 10<sup>th</sup> percentile) by 2020.</p><p> </p><p> </p><p>[1] <a href="https://www.gov.uk/government/news/today-britain-gets-a-pay-rise-thanks-to-the-national-living-wage" target="_blank">https://www.gov.uk/government/news/today-britain-gets-a-pay-rise-thanks-to-the-national-living-wage</a></p>","Stourbridge","Margot James",,"2016-08-10T07:01:08.343Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/536188/answer","Biography information for Margot James","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/536188/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/536188/answer",,,,,"201","Business, Energy and Industrial Strategy","Business, Energy and Industrial Strategy","2016-07-13","Equal Pay","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Business, Energy and Industrial Strategy, if he will make an assessment of the potential effect of the introduction of the new minimum wage on (a) evening and weekend working pay rates for women and (b) gender pay equality.","false","Biography information for Helen Jones","Warrington North","Helen Jones","42657"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/536189","Department for Work and Pensions","false","2016-07-19","<p>The Department introduced the independent audit of Work Capability Assessments in March 2015 in line with the start of the new Health and Disability Assessment Service contract.</p><p> </p><p>Audit has a central role in confirming that independent health professional advice complies with the required standards and that it is clear and medically reasonable. It also provides assurance that any approach to assessment and opinion given is consistent so that, irrespective of where or by whom the assessment is carried out, claimants with conditions that have the same functional effect will ultimately receive the same benefit outcome.</p><p><strong> </strong></p>","Portsmouth North","Penny Mordaunt",,"2016-07-19T13:22:29.67Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/536189/answer","Biography information for Penny Mordaunt","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/536189/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/536189/answer",,,,,"29","Work and Pensions","Work and Pensions","2016-07-13","Work Capability Assessment","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Work and Pensions, what steps his Department takes to ensure that the level of functional impairment is adequately assessed to provide appropriate support for a claimant to obtain employment.","false","Biography information for Dr Lisa Cameron","East Kilbride, Strathaven and Lesmahagow","Dr Lisa Cameron","42659"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/536190","Department for Work and Pensions","false","2016-07-21","<p>Details of the evidence base and consultative group members involved in the development of the Work Capability Assessment can be found in the Transformation of the Personal Capability assessment reports of September 2006, February 2007 and November 2007.</p><p><strong> </strong></p><p><a href="http://webarchive.nationalarchives.gov.uk/20090605153301/http:/www.workandpensions.gov.uk/welfarereform/pca.asp" target="_blank"><strong>http://webarchive.nationalarchives.gov.uk/20090605153301/http:/www.workandpensions.gov.uk/welfarereform/pca.asp</strong></a></p>","Portsmouth North","Penny Mordaunt","42709","2016-07-21T13:25:23.583Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/536190/answer","Biography information for Penny Mordaunt","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/536190/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/536190/answer",,,,,"29","Work and Pensions","Work and Pensions","2016-07-13","Work Capability Assessment","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Work and Pensions, if he will publish the evidence base for the choice of descriptors used in work capability assessments.","false","Biography information for Dr Lisa Cameron","East Kilbride, Strathaven and Lesmahagow","Dr Lisa Cameron","42660"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/536192","Department for Work and Pensions","false","2016-07-18","<p>The data collected under the Health and Social Care Information Centre (Statements of Fitness for Work) Directions 2015 will be non patient identifiable on extraction and anonymous on publication, and will not contain any personal information that can be used to identify individuals. Additional measures such as aggregation of disease codes and small number suppression will also be applied which means that, for published information, any number less than five will be replaced by a star.</p>","Portsmouth North","Penny Mordaunt",,"2016-07-18T16:36:38.573Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/536192/answer","Biography information for Penny Mordaunt","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/536192/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/536192/answer",,,,,"29","Work and Pensions","Work and Pensions","2016-07-13","Fit for Work Scheme","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Work and Pensions, whether the Fitness for Work data his Department receives from GPs, collected under the Health and Social Care Information Centre (Statements of Fitness for Work) Directions 2015, is considered identifiable personal data by his Department.","false","Biography information for Mr Roger Godsiff","Birmingham, Hall Green","Mr Roger Godsiff","42639"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/536193","Department for Work and Pensions","false","2016-07-19","<p>Full impact and equality impact assessments will be undertaken in due course.</p><p> </p><p>Single people under 35 will be exempt from the Shared Accommodation Rate if they fall into one of the categories below:</p><ul><li>They have children or a non-dependent living with them;</li><li>They qualify for a severe disability premium;</li><li>If they have left care and are under the age of 22;</li><li>If they have an extra bedroom for a non-resident carer providing overnight care;</li><li>If they are a foster carer;</li><li>They are aged 25 to 34 years old and have spent at least 3 months in a homeless hostel or hostel specialising in rehabilitation and resettlement;</li><li>They are aged 25 to 34 years old who are an ex-offender managed under a multi-agency MAPPA agreement.</li></ul><p>For those who are not covered by these exemptions, they will be able to apply for Discretionary Housing Payments if they need help meeting the shortfall in their rent.</p>","Romsey and Southampton North","Caroline Nokes",,"2016-07-19T15:20:00.567Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/536193/answer","Biography information for Caroline Nokes","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/536193/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/536193/answer",,,,,"29","Work and Pensions","Work and Pensions","2016-07-13","Housing Benefit: Social Rented Housing","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Work and Pensions, what assessment his Department has made of the potential effect of extending the Shared Accommodation Rate to social rented housing on the ability of single people under the age of 35 to access general needs social rented housing.","false","Biography information for Dr Eilidh Whiteford","Banff and Buchan","Dr Eilidh Whiteford","42599"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/536194","Department for Work and Pensions","false","2016-07-18","<p>The information requested is not readily available and to provide it would incur disproportionate cost.</p><p>Information on Jobseeker’s Allowance and Employment and Support Allowance sanction decisions, by cumulative frequency and geography, is available here: <a href="https://stat-xplore.dwp.gov.uk/" target="_blank">https://stat-xplore.dwp.gov.uk/</a></p><p>Guidance on how to extract the information required can be found at:</p><p><a href="https://sw.stat-xplore.dwp.gov.uk/webapi/online-help/Getting-Started---SuperWEB2.html" target="_blank">https://sw.stat-xplore.dwp.gov.uk/webapi/online-help/Getting-Started---SuperWEB2.html</a></p>","East Hampshire","Damian Hinds",,"2016-07-18T14:06:03.173Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/536194/answer","Biography information for Mr Damian Hinds","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/536194/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/536194/answer",,,,,"29","Work and Pensions","Work and Pensions","2016-07-13","Social Security Benefits: Fife","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Work and Pensions, how many benefit claimants were sanctioned more than once in (a) Fife and (b) Kirkcaldy and Cowdenbeath constituency in (i) 2011-12, (ii) 2012-13, (iii) 2013-14, (iv) 2014-15 and (v) 2015-16.","false","Biography information for Roger Mullin","Kirkcaldy and Cowdenbeath","Roger Mullin","42627"
